			<!-- ── Chapter 5: The Architecture of Intention ──────────── -->
			<div class="book-page">
				<span class="page-number" aria-hidden="true">12</span>
				<div class="chapter-header">
					<span class="chapter-label">Chapter Five</span>
					<h2 class="chapter-title">The Architecture of Intention</h2>
				</div>

				<div class="book-text">
					<p>
						Peter Gollwitzer and Paschal Sheeran&rsquo;s 2006 meta-analysis
						of 94 studies with over 8,000 participants found that
						<em>implementation intentions</em> &mdash; specific if-then plans
						&mdash; have an effect size of d&thinsp;=&thinsp;0.65. Difficult
						goals are completed three times more often when paired with
						if-then plans.
					</p>
					<p>
						The format is simple: &ldquo;If [situation], then I will
						[action].&rdquo; This automates behavior at the point of decision,
						bypassing willpower entirely. The plan pre-loads the response,
						so the environment triggers the action.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="stat-callout observe-fade">
					<span class="stat-number">78%</span>
					<p class="stat-description">
						Goal achievement rate when using financial stakes plus a referee,
						compared to 35% without commitment devices.
					</p>
					<cite class="stat-cite">stickK / Yale University research</cite>
				</div>

				<div class="book-text">
					<p>
						Katherine Milkman&rsquo;s 2014 research on <em>temptation
						bundling</em> showed 51% more gym visits when participants
						could only access enjoyable audiobooks while exercising &mdash;
						linking &ldquo;want&rdquo; to &ldquo;should.&rdquo;
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="book-page">
				<span class="page-number" aria-hidden="true">13</span>

				<div class="book-text">
					<p>
						DeskTime&rsquo;s analysis of their top 10% most productive users
						revealed a consistent pattern: 52 minutes of focused work followed
						by 17 minutes of rest. The key was not the exact ratio but the
						principle &mdash; sprints of intense purpose paired with breaks
						of complete disengagement.
					</p>
					<p>
						You are three times more likely to achieve a goal with commitment
						devices &mdash; mechanisms that make the cost of inaction concrete
						and immediate. The architecture of intention is not about
						willpower. It is about designing systems that make the right
						action the easiest one.
					</p>
				</div>

				<!-- Illustration: Clock / geometric hourglass -->
				<figure class="book-illustration" aria-label="Geometric clock illustration">
					<svg class="focus-illustration" viewBox="0 0 180 180" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-hidden="true">
						<!-- Clock circle -->
						<circle cx="90" cy="90" r="65" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.35"></circle>
						<!-- Hour marks -->
						<line x1="90" y1="30" x2="90" y2="38" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.4"></line>
						<line x1="150" y1="90" x2="142" y2="90" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.4"></line>
						<line x1="90" y1="150" x2="90" y2="142" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.4"></line>
						<line x1="30" y1="90" x2="38" y2="90" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.4"></line>
						<!-- Hour hand -->
