						<!-- Minute hand -->
						<line x1="90" y1="90" x2="126" y2="72" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.45"></line>
						<!-- Center dot -->
						<circle cx="90" cy="90" r="3" fill="currentColor" opacity="0.5"></circle>
					</svg>
					<figcaption class="illustration-caption">
						Structured time
					</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</div>

			<!-- ── Chapter 6: Environment & Play ─────────────────────── -->
			<div class="book-page">
				<span class="page-number" aria-hidden="true">14</span>
				<div class="chapter-header">
					<span class="chapter-label">Chapter Six</span>
					<h2 class="chapter-title">Environment &amp; Play</h2>
				</div>

				<div class="book-text">
					<p>
						Mehta, Zhu, and Cheema (2012) found that ambient noise at 70
						decibels &mdash; roughly the level of a coffee shop &mdash;
						enhances creative performance by promoting abstract thinking.
						At 85 decibels, performance drops sharply. There is a sweet
						spot of productive distraction.
					</p>
					<p>
						A Cornell study by Hedge (2017) found that workers with adequate
						natural light reported an 84% drop in eyestrain symptoms and a
						10% decrease in drowsiness. Our cognitive performance is
						profoundly shaped by the physical environment we inhabit.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="book-page">
				<span class="page-number" aria-hidden="true">15</span>

				<div class="book-text">
					<p>
						Stuart Brown&rsquo;s research on play began in an unlikely place:
						the 1966 University of Texas tower shooting. Investigating the
						perpetrator&rsquo;s background, Brown found severe play deprivation.
						He went on to study over 6,000 life histories and found that play
						deprivation is consistently linked to antisocial behavior,
						depression, and rigidity.
					</p>
					<p>
						Jaak Panksepp&rsquo;s neuroscience research identified PLAY as
						one of seven hardwired emotional systems in the mammalian brain.
						His work showed that rats literally laugh during play &mdash;
						ultrasonic chirps at 50 kHz. Play impulses originate in the brain
						stem, making them among the most ancient and fundamental drives
						we possess.
					</p>
					<p>
						Children who play are faster learners, more creative, and more
						socially competent. Adults who play are more resilient, more
						innovative, and more collaborative. Play is not the opposite
						of work &mdash; it is work&rsquo;s essential companion.
					</p>
				</div>

